            "author_info": {
                "name": "Barak Diba",
                "href": "/profile/Barak-Diba"
            },
            "answer_text": "During engagement while charging, soldiers are train to give fire and advance, alongside being in contact with their friends. Updating other soldiers of the situation/ passing order/ notifying relevant thing is very crucial. Now think you have to do it perfectly: remember the message, pass it correctly, wait for a sign that the receiver got it, inform the one who sent you the message that the message was conveyed. All of that for only one message, not including: The stress you are in.The distance between the soldiers (could be very big).The fact that while doing so you actually need to aim and fire accurate at the enemy.The loud noise of several guns in your surrounding + yours firing without an end and without notice which makes you unable to hear anything clearly.Good luck doing so in those conditions. So back to the question: How do soldiers reference enemy positions to each other in combat? You shout. You don't only shout, but actually you are screaming every little thing. If you have done such drill and your throat doesn't hurt- clearly you did it wrong, regardless of how much did you hit. Charging is more about teamwork than \u201chow good at you at shooting\u201d.  As for how actually you notify your friends of an enemy is new position, just use one of this: Give a simple and short description of the enemy's place.Give an approximate distance and an angle from your friends\u2019 eyes / yours (depends on the parameters).If you can and have that luxury, the most accurate way is to give coordinates from GPS/map/other position locating equipment.If you need to inform other forces not currently near you, use the radio. There are specific different ways to do so in case of: infantry, helicopters, tanks, mortars, artillery\u2026 ",
